2 Requirement Description

Genes are clustered and then annotated on the graph. Needless to say, you need to have the same data as the original text, as long as you enter the data to get a similar graph.

From https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S2352396421003340?via%3Dihub

Fig. 1. Prognostic stratification of PDAC through their GT gene expression profile (a, b) and clinical features of patients with their PDAC molecular profiles (c, d). (a) Biplot of the HCPC analysis result based on RNA-seq data of 74 PDAC and 169 GT genes.

## kmeans by row. kmeaninput matrix()
## kmeans by row. Note that the kmean function is clustered by row, so here you need to transpose it, input matrix behavior samples, and list as traits (genes)
k2 <- kmeans(
  x = t(data2), #sample # If your data is a behavioral sample, listed as a gene, you don't need to transpose it
  centers = 2 #  # Set the number of clusters
)

## PCA by rowprcompinput matrixkmeans
## PCA by row,The input matrix of the prcomp function is the same as that of kmeans
pca <- prcomp(t(data2))

6 Start drawing

7 : factoextra Method 1: Call the factoextra package

p <- fviz_pca_ind(
  X = pca, 
  repel = T, 
  geom = c("point", "text"), # ,text # If you don't want the text tag, just remove the text
  habillage = k2$cluster, #  # Add group information
  legend.title = "cluster", #  # Legend title
  mean.point = FALSE, #  # Whether to add a cluster center
  palette = c("red","blue"), # change color, map to col.ind
  pointsize = 2.5, #  # The size of the dot
  addEllipses = TRUE, #  # Add an outer border
  ellipse.type = "convex", # , "convex" # Outer Border Type, Convex Polygon "Convex"
  axes.linetype = "blank", # hide zerolines
  ggtheme = theme_classic(base_size = 15) # ggplot # ggplot theme
)
# remove text legend
p <- p + guides(color = guide_legend(override.aes = aes(label = "")))
# theme
p + theme(
  legend.position = "top",
  plot.title = element_blank(),
  axis.text = element_text(color = "black")
)
## Ignoring unknown labels:
##  linetype : "cluster"

ggsave("PCA_factoextra.pdf")

7.1 : ggplot Method 2: ggplot

data.use <- as.data.frame(pca$x[, c("PC1", "PC2")])
data.use$cluster <- factor(k2$cluster)
data.use$name <- rownames(data.use)

vars.percent <- pca$sdev^2 / sum(pca$sdev^2) #  # Calculate the variance of the data for different principal component explanations
dims <- c(1,2) # PC1PC2 # Select PC1 and PC2 for visualization
xlab <- paste0("Dim1 (", round(vars.percent[dims[1]]*100, 1), "%)")
ylab <- paste0("Dim2 (", round(vars.percent[dims[2]]*100, 1), "%)")
colors.use <- c("red", "blue")

Drawing

ggplot(data.use, aes(PC1, PC2, shape=cluster, color=cluster)) + 
  geom_point(size = 2.5) + 
  geom_convexhull(aes(fill=cluster), alpha = 0.15) + 
  ggrepel::geom_text_repel(
    aes(label=name), 
    size = 3, 
    max.iter = 2000, # text overlapmax.iter # If there are too many samples and the text overlap cannot be solved, you can increase the max.iter parameter
    show.legend = F) + 
  scale_color_manual(values = colors.use) + 
  scale_fill_manual(values = colors.use) + 
  labs(x = xlab, y = ylab) + 
  theme_classic(base_size = 15) + 
  theme(
    legend.position = "top",
    plot.title = element_blank(),
    axis.text = element_text(color = "black")
  )

ggsave("PCA_ggplot2.pdf")
